
@startuml

' Define the classes and their attributes
class Faculty {
    - name: String
    - numberOfInstitutes: int
    - dean: Employee
}

class Institute {
    - name: String
    - address: String
}

class Employee {
    - socialSecurityNumber: String
    - name: String
    - email: String
    + type: String (Research or Administrative)
}

class ResearchAssistant {
    - fieldOfResearch: String
    - projects: List<Project>
    - coursesTaught: List<Course>
    -- extends Employee
}

class Project {
    - name: String
    - startDate: Date
    - endDate: Date
    - hours: int
}

class Course {
    - courseID: String
    - name: String
    - weeklyDuration: int
}

' Relationships

Faculty "1" -- "0..*" Institute : consists of
Institute "1" -- "1" Faculty : belongs to

Employee "1" -- "1" Faculty : dean (optional)
Employee "1" -- "0..*" Institute : works at
Employee "1" -- "0..*" Project : involved in
Employee "1" -- "0..*" Course : teaches

ResearchAssistant --|> Employee : is a type of
ResearchAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Project : involved in
ResearchAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Course : teaches

@enduml

### Notes:
- `Faculty` has a reference to its `dean`, who is an `Employee`.
- `Institute` is part of a `Faculty`.
- `Employee` is a base class for both `ResearchAssistant` and administrative staff.
- `ResearchAssistant` can be involved in multiple `Projects` and may also teach `Courses`.
- Each `Project` has a name, start date, end date, and number of hours.
- Each `Course` has a unique ID, name, and weekly duration.

